            <div type="apparatus" resp="#martaf">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text based on photograph</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 1"><note>Korhonen: [Β]ενερ[ιος] (or another Latin name such as Venerianus or Generosus)</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 2"><note>Korhonen: [τελευτήσα]ς</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#martaf">
                <p>… Benerios (?) …, having died 3 days before …</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>… Benerios (?) …, morto 3 giorni prima di …</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#martaf">
                <p>It is impossible to determine with certainty the structure of this Christian epitaph because of its fragmentary nature: Korhonen restores at l. 1 the name of the deceased, <foreign xml:lang="grc">Βενέριος</foreign> (<foreign xml:lang="la">Venerius</foreign>), οr another Greek equivalent of the Latin names <foreign xml:lang="la">Venerianus</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="la">Generosus</foreign>, at l. 2 the indication of the date of death. For the indication of the date of death, the participle of <foreign xml:lang="grc">τελευτάω</foreign> is quite rare in Christian epitaphs, but a similar structure can be found in some inscriptions from Syracuse and in Catania in IG 14.545 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001364">ISic001364</ref>.</p>
            </div>
